    "long_instructions": "The <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Customer</code> class declares an instance variable for a 1D array of <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">double</code> values to store the amounts a customer spent on their previous purchases.\r\n\r\n✅ **TO DO:** In <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">CustomerRunner.java</code>, instantiate a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Customer</code> object with a 1D array that stores **5** <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">double</code> values.\r\n\r\n1. Declare and initialize a 1D array to store **5** <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">double</code> values.\r\n\r\n2. Instantiate a <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Customer</code> object by passing the 1D array as the argument to the constructor.\r\n\r\n3. Print the <code style=\"background-color: #ececec; color: black; font-weight: bold;\">Customer</code> object.\r\n\r\n<div style=\"background-color: #E0D1EC; border: 1px solid #9660bf; border-radius: 5px; font-size: 1.1em; padding: 15px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">\r\n💡 <strong>TIP:</strong> Check out the <strong>Help & Tips</strong> tab ⬆️ for help with declaring and initializing a 1D array.\r\n</div>\r\n\r\n## ***Don't forget to . . .***\r\n\r\n![](https://images.code.org/eb2c8910ae2e150019b8e2177405d4af-image-1668191576873.png)",
